Week 1

Introduction

We can store categorical responses as factors:

x <- c("yes","no","yes","yes","no","maybe","maybe")
class(x)
## [1] "character"
y <- factor(x)
summary(y)
## maybe    no   yes 
##     2     2     3
table(x)
## x
## maybe    no   yes 
##     2     2     3

We can also have numerical variables:

inc <- c(1000,3000,500,200,14,25,345)

We can apply a function to people based on their responses:

tapply(inc,x,mean)
##     maybe        no       yes 
##  185.0000 1507.0000  566.6667

Moving on to matrix multiplication:

z <- matrix(c(5,7,9,6,3,4),nrow=3,ncol=2)
y <- matrix(c(1,3,0,9,5,-1),nrow=3,ncol=2)
# We can do term-by-term multiplication
z*y
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    5   54
## [2,]   21   15
## [3,]    0   -4
# get transpose
t(y)
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    3    0
## [2,]    9    5   -1
# matrix multiply
z%*%t(y)
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]   59   45   -6
## [2,]   34   36   -3
## [3,]   45   47   -4

Linear Algebra

Solving equations:

a <- array(c(2,1,-1,2),c(2,2))
b <- c(4,4)
solve(a,b)
## [1] 2.4 0.8

The solve(a,b) command solves the system of linear equations: \[ \mathbf{A}\vec{x}=b \] It returns the vector \(\vec{x}\).

t <- eigen(a) # get eigendecomposition
t$values      # eigenvalues
## [1] 2+1i 2-1i
t$vectors     # eigenvectors
##                      [,1]                 [,2]
## [1,] 0.7071068+0.0000000i 0.7071068+0.0000000i
## [2,] 0.0000000-0.7071068i 0.0000000+0.7071068i

We start plotting

plot(wine$VINT,wine$LPRICE)

pairs(wine)

We can take a deeper look int the data by subsetting it

winetrain <- subset(wine,wine$VINT <= 1978 & !is.na(wine$LPRICE))
winetest <- subset(wine,wine$VINT > 1978)

We are going to use linear regression, which is the following model: \[ y_{i}=\beta_{0}+\sum_{j}\beta{j}x_{ij}+\epsilon_{i}\\ \min_{\beta_{j},\forall j} \sum_{i}\left(y_{i}-\beta-\beta_{j}x_{ij}\right)\\ \forall i \in N, \forall j \in M \]

Now let’s take the linear model

model <- lm(LPRICE~VINT,winetrain)
summary(model)
